\begin_layout Subsection
Outcome Variables
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:outcome-variables"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We measure outcomes at three levels of the value chain.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At the MCC level,
 primary outcomes capture the adoption of quality testing infrastructure and the emergence of quality-based pricing.
 Testing outcomes include whether the MCC uses the milk analyzer to test incoming milk deliveries and whether it tests outgoing milk sold to processors.
 Pricing outcomes include the average price paid to farmers for milk,
 the average price received from buyers,
 and whether the MCC gives or receives quality-based bonuses.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At the farmer level,
 primary outcomes capture changes in production practices and market returns.
 These include an index of improved dairy management practices (oversowing,
 legume pastures,
 controlled grazing,
 pasture conservation,
 and supplementary feeding),
 whether the farmer's buyer uses a milk analyzer for quality testing,
 the quantity-weighted average sales price received,
 and whether the farmer receives a quality bonus from any buyer.
 We combine these four outcomes into an Anderson index as a summary measure.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally,
 to obtain objective measures of milk quality,
 we collect supervised milk samples at endline.
 Enumerators equipped with milk analyzers visited each MCC and tested all incoming deliveries over one full day,
 yielding measurements of butterfat,
 solids-not-fat,
 protein,
 added water,
 and corrected lactometer reading for each delivery.
 These visits were unannounced.
 To limit information spillovers,
 the testing was conducted over a short period with as many enumerators deployed simultaneously as possible.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This exercise posed logistical challenges,
 as MCCs opened early (usually at 8:00 am) and were often in remote areas.
 Enumerators frequently stayed overnight nearby to set up equipment before deliveries and carried generators for use where power was unavailable.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Secondary outcome families,
 reported in the appendix,
 include sales quantities,
 treatment uptake indicators,
 sales channel choices,
 and MCC-level farmer counts and volumes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Estimation and Inference
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Estimation-and-inference"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We estimate intent-to-treat (ITT) effects using ordinary least squares with Analysis of Covariance (ANCOVA) specifications that control for baseline values of the outcome where available.
 At the MCC level,
 denote milk collection centers by 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{m}$
\end_inset

 be a treatment indicator equal to one if MCC 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 was assigned to receive the quality measurement and monitoring system.
 The MCC-level estimating equation is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y_{m}=\alpha+\beta T_{m}+\gamma y^{b}_{m}+\varepsilon_{m}\label{eq:mcc}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{m}$
\end_inset

 is the outcome of interest,
 
\begin_inset Formula $y^{b}_{m}$
\end_inset

 is its baseline value,
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 is the parameter of interest.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At the farmer level,
 let 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i,m}$
\end_inset

 denote the outcome for farmer 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 in the catchment area of MCC 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y_{i,m}=\alpha+\beta T_{i,m}+\gamma y^{b}_{i,m}+\varepsilon_{i,m}\label{eq:farmer}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{i,m}$
\end_inset

 indicates whether farmer 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

's MCC was assigned to treatment and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{i,m}$
\end_inset

 is an error term that may be correlated within catchment areas.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For supervised milk samples collected at endline,
 we estimate treatment effects using quantity-weighted least squares:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
q_{j,m}=\alpha+\beta T_{m}+\varepsilon_{j,m}\label{eq:samples}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{j,m}$
\end_inset

 is the quality measure for milk delivery 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 at MCC 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

,
 weighted by the quantity delivered.
 No baseline control is available for these outcomes as supervised quality testing was conducted only at endline.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We report point estimates and CR2 cluster-robust standard errors 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "imbens2016robust"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 clustered at the MCC catchment area level,
 for effect size interpretation.
 To summarize effects across multiple outcomes within a family,
 we construct Anderson indices 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "anderson2008multiple"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Statistical inference is based on Fisher randomization inference (RI).
 Using the OLS coefficient as the test statistic,
 we evaluate its significance against a permutation distribution generated from 5,000 reassignments of treatment at the MCC catchment level,
 maintaining the number of treated clusters.
 Because the permutation scheme mirrors the actual randomization,
 the resulting p-values are exact and do not depend on asymptotic approximations or assumptions about within-cluster correlation or the number of clusters.
 To account for multiple testing across outcomes within a family,
 we apply Westfall-Young stepdown adjustments 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "westfall1993resampling"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 using the same permutation distribution,
 controlling the familywise error rate while exploiting the correlation structure across outcomes.
 CR2-based p-values and Anderson-Sharp q-values are reported in the appendix.
\end_layout

