\begin_layout Standard
The treatment-on-the-treated (LATE) estimates,
 presented in Appendix Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Primary-outcomes-milk-quality-LATE"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 for completeness,
 are generally less precisely estimated than the intention-to-treat (ITT) effects.
 The instrument only shifts the probability that an MCC consistently uses the analyzer,
 and the first stage is mechanically weaker than the underlying ITT assignment.
 As a result,
 the 2SLS estimator inflates sampling variability because it attributes all treatment effects to the subset of MCCs that actually complied with analyzer use.
 Moreover,
 if assignment affects outcomes partly through channels other than actual machine use (such as expectations,
 monitoring incentives,
 or changes in manager behavior),
 then the instrument captures only a fraction of the relevant variation,
 further reducing precision.
 Together,
 these factors imply wider confidence intervals for the LATE relative to the more precise ITT estimates.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consistent with this,
 the LATE point estimates in Appendix Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Primary-outcomes-milk-quality-LATE"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 are roughly two to three times larger than the corresponding ITT coefficients,
 reflecting the rescaling by the compliance rate.
 The composite quality index remains statistically significant at the 5 percent level under 2SLS,
 and the individual estimates for fat content and density (CLR) are marginally significant,
 while added water,
 SNF,
 and protein lose statistical significance despite retaining the expected signs.
 The qualitative conclusions are thus unchanged:
 actual analyzer use improves milk composition,
 but the effects are estimated with considerably less precision.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Farmer Level
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:farmer-level"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We also define four primary outcomes at the farmer level and combine them into an index to assess the overall impact of the intervention on farmer-level outcomes.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first outcome is a composite in itself,
 and measures production investment and management practices that are expected to improve milk quality.
 We construct an 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "anderson2008multiple"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 index from farmer reports on six recommended practices undertaken in the past year:
 (i) over-sowing new fields with improved forage grasses such as 
\emph on
Napier
\emph default
,
 
\emph on
Brachiaria
\emph default
,
 or 
\emph on
Rhodes
\emph default
 grasses;
 (ii) using legume pastures such as 
\emph on
Centro
\emph default
,
 
\emph on
Siratro
\emph default
,
 or 
\emph on
Desmodium
\emph default
;
 (iii) adopting controlled or zero grazing during the last dry season;
 (iv) practicing pasture conservation through hay,
 silage,
 or haylage;
 and (v) using feed supplements such as maize bran,
 crop residues (for example banana peelings),
 or mineral licks.
 This index summarizes the extent to which farmers adjusted production strategies in response to the intervention.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The second outcome captures whether buyers actively checked milk quality at the point of transaction.
 Here,
 we distinguish between different categories of buyers (e.g.,
 MCCs,
 processor,
 trader,
 etc.) and ask if milk was tested using a milk analyzer if the farmer sold milk to this particular buyer in the 7 days prior to the survey.
 The indicator is true if milk sold in the last 7 days was tested by at least one buyer.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The third outcome is the price received for milk sold.
 Specifically,
 we record the average price per liter obtained in the farmer’s most recent sale during the past seven days,
 inclusive of any quality premiums.
 Farmers reported prices by buyer category,
 and we construct a weighted average across categories using transaction volumes as weights.
 We also directly ask whether the buyer pays a higher price for higher-quality milk.
 This question was posed in general terms,
 without reference to a specific time frame.
 These outcomes capture whether quality improvements translate into tangible financial benefits for farmers.
\end_layout

