 and
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Secondary-outcomes-farmer-uptake"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
 At the MCC level,
 the treatment produced large and precisely estimated effects on technology presence and use.
 Treated MCCs are significantly more likely to display project posters publicizing the analyzers,
 to have a functioning milk analyzer on site (an increase of roughly 53 percentage points),
 and to use digital record-keeping tools for quality and quantity data.
 These results confirm both compliance with treatment assignment and the persistence of the hardware and associated practices at treated sites.
 The adoption of digital record-keeping is particularly noteworthy,
 as it addresses the traceability and transparency that are prerequisites for quality-linked transactions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At the farmer level,
 we find no evidence that the intervention affected secondary uptake outcomes,
 including seed usage or understanding of compositional quality.
 This is consistent with the intervention design:
 the treatment targeted technology adoption at collection centers,
 not farmer education.
 Improved analyzer use at MCCs did not spill over into farmer knowledge or practice,
 reinforcing the interpretation that the intervention operated through the enforcement channel at the MCC level rather than through changes in farmer behavior.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
A Model of Quality Infrastructure and Quality Incentives
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:model"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This section presents a simple analytical framework to rationalize the findings from the experiment.
 The model formalizes two channels through which quality infrastructure can affect outcomes:
 an enforcement channel,
 in which improved measurement precision makes rejection thresholds credibly binding,
 and a price channel,
 in which quality measurement enables quality-differentiated pricing.
 The main experiment results are consistent with the enforcement channel operating in isolation:
 quality improves but prices do not differentiate.
 We then present results from a follow-up experiment that tests the price channel directly by exogenously activating quality-based premiums.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Environment and Timing
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is one processor,
 multiple MCCs indexed by 
\emph on
m
\emph default
,
 and,
 within each MCC catchment,
 multiple farmers indexed by 
\emph on
i
\emph default
 that deliver milk to the MCC.
 The quantity of milk supplied by farmer 
\emph on
i
\emph default
,
 denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i}$
\end_inset

,
 is assumed to be fixed in the short run,
 as it primarily depends on the farmer’s herd size,
 which does not adjust quickly.
 Milk quality is expressed on a continuum 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(q_{i}\in\left[0,1\right]\right)$
\end_inset

 and reflects compositional attributes such as butterfat and SNF.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After observing delivered quantities and a (possibly noisy) signal of quality for each farmer,
 the MCC decides whether to accept or reject each delivery.
 Accepted milk is aggregated and sold to the processor,
 who pays a premium for verifiable compositional quality.
 The downstream price received by the MCC therefore depends on average quality of accepted milk.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A critical feature of the model is how the MCC observes quality.
 Without measurement technology,
 the MCC observes a noisy signal of farmer
\emph on
 i
\emph default
's quality:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
s_{i}=q_{i}+\eta_{i}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{i}\sim N(0,\sigma^{2})$
\end_inset

 is measurement noise.
 With only basic tools (lactometer,
 alcohol test),
 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

 is large:
 the MCC can detect gross adulteration but cannot precisely assess compositional quality.
 The introduction of a milk analyzer reduces 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

 toward zero,
 enabling precise measurement of butterfat,
 SNF,
 protein,
 and added water.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The acceptance decision is based on the observed signal:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
a_{i}=\mathbf{1}\left\{ s_{i}\geq q_{min}\right\} 
\end{equation}

\end_inset

rather than true quality 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 This distinction is central:
 when 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

 is high,
 the acceptance threshold is only weakly enforced because the MCC cannot reliably distinguish high-quality from low-quality milk.
 Reducing 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

 makes the threshold bite.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Farmers are connected to the MCC either directly or through intermediaries,
 which may affect the extent to which downstream quality incentives reach them.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Production of Quality at the Farm
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Each farmer 
\emph on
i
\emph default
 supplies a fixed quantity of milk 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i}$
\end_inset

 in the short run and chooses effort 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{i}\geq0$
\end_inset

 that affects the compositional quality of milk:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
q_{i}=\theta_{i}e_{i}+\varepsilon_{i}\label{eq:quality}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
with 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{i}\geq0$
\end_inset

 capturing how effectively effort is translated into quality,
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{i}$
\end_inset

 a mean-zero shock.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Effort is assumed to be costly,
 which we model as a quadratic function:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
c_{i}(e_{i})=\frac{k_{i}}{2}e^{2}_{i}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
with 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{i}>0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Prices,
 Pass-Through,
 and Intermediation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let the processor pay the MCC a unit price 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
p_{m}=\bar{p}+\alpha\,\bar{q}_{m}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{q}_{m}$
\end_inset

 is average quality in MCC 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\geq0$
\end_inset

 is the per-unit premium slope for verifiable quality.
 In practice,
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 depends on whether the MCC can credibly demonstrate quality to the processor.
 When
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

 is high,
 the MCC cannot verify its own quality and has no basis to negotiate quality-differentiated prices;
 processors,
 in turn,
 have little reason to offer quality premiums if upstream infrastructure cannot reliably deliver consistent compositional quality.
 When
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

 falls,
 two things change.
 First,
 the MCC acquires verifiable quality information that strengthens its bargaining position:
 it can credibly demonstrate to the processor that its milk exceeds the market average and can approach competing buyers with evidence.
 Second,
 processors may find it worthwhile to offer quality-differentiated contracts because upstream measurement infrastructure makes consistent delivery credible.
 Whether
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 actually increases depends on whether these conditions are sufficient to overcome contracting frictions,
 processor market power,
 and coordination failures.
 A central question of this paper is whether equipping MCCs with analyzers is sufficient to activate
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha>0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The MCC posts a pricing rule that links observed quality 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(q_{i}\right)$
\end_inset

 to price paid to farmers 
