\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
p_{i}=p_{0}+\lambda_{i}\alpha\,q_{i}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0}$
\end_inset

 is a base price,
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq\lambda_{i}\leq1$
\end_inset

 is the pass-through rate of the premium to farmer 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In principle,
 the extent to which the MCC passes through the quality premium to farmers is the outcome of a profit-maximization problem:
 the MCC would optimally choose a pass-through rate that balances retaining a share of the downstream premium against inducing higher farmer effort and thus higher average quality.
 For tractability and to keep the conceptual model focused on testable predictions,
 we treat 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{i}$
\end_inset

 as a reduced-form parameter summarizing institutional frictions,
 bargaining power,
 and local contracting norms
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Pass-through depends on local contracting frictions,
 transparency,
 and the structure of intermediation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Farmer Optimization
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The MCC may reject milk that does not meet a minimum quality standard.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}\in\left\{ 0,1\right\} $
\end_inset

 be an acceptance indicator,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}=1$
\end_inset

 if farmer
\emph on
i
\emph default
's observed signal meets a minimum quality threshold 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{min}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}=0$
\end_inset

 otherwise:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
a_{i}=\mathbf{1}\left\{ s_{i}\geq q_{min}\right\} 
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Farmer 
\emph on
i
\emph default
’s realized revenue is then
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
r_{i}\left(e_{i}\right)=a_{i}p_{i}\left(q_{i}\right)y_{i}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Because both quality and its observation include noise,
 acceptance is uncertain from the farmer’s perspective.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}=q_{i}+\eta_{i}=\theta_{i}e_{i}+\varepsilon_{i}+\eta_{i}$
\end_inset

,
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{i}$
\end_inset

 are independent,
 the acceptance probability can be written as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\pi_{i}\left(e_{i};q_{min},\sigma^{2}\right)=\Pr\left(s_{i}\geq q_{min}|e_{i}\right)=1-\Phi\left(\frac{q_{min}-\theta_{i}e_{i}}{\sqrt{\sigma^{2}_{\varepsilon}+\sigma^{2}}}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi$
\end_inset

 is the standard normal CDF and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}_{\varepsilon}$
\end_inset

 is the variance of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 This makes explicit that reducing 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

 (better measurement) tightens the acceptance probability around the threshold.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The acceptance probability is increasing in effort:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial\pi_{i}\left(e_{i};q_{min},\sigma^{2}\right)}{\partial e_{i}}>0
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Farmer 
\emph on
i
\emph default
’s expected revenue is therefore
\end_layout

