\begin_layout Subsubsection
Effect of Improved Measurement Precision
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The central comparative static for the main experiment concerns the effect of reducing measurement noise
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Consider the acceptance probability:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\pi_{i}\left(e_{i};q_{min},\sigma^{2}\right)=1-\Phi\left(\frac{q_{min}-\theta_{i}e_{i}}{\sqrt{\sigma^{2}_{\varepsilon}+\sigma^{2}}}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Reducing 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

 (improving measurement precision) has two effects.
 First,
 for farmers whose expected quality 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{i}e_{i}$
\end_inset

 is close to but above the threshold 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{min}$
\end_inset

,
 acceptance becomes more certain,
 reducing the risk of false rejection.
 Second,
 and more importantly,
 for farmers whose expected quality is near or below the threshold,
 the probability of rejection increases sharply.
 The threat of rejection,
 previously weakened by the noise in the MCC's observation,
 becomes credible.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This tightening of the acceptance probability distribution around the threshold generates an incentive for farmers near the margin to increase effort:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial e^{*}_{i}}{\partial\sigma^{2}}<0\quad\text{when }\theta_{i}e_{i}\text{ is near }q_{min}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

That is,
 better measurement (lower 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

) induces higher effort from farmers who are close to the acceptance threshold.
 Crucially,
 this mechanism operates entirely through the extensive margin (acceptance probability) and does not require any price differentiation (
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 can be zero).
 The model therefore predicts that measurement technology can improve quality purely through more credible enforcement,
 without any change in the price schedule.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is the enforcement channel.
 Its key empirical signatures are:
 (i) quality improves,
 particularly through reduced adulteration (the quality dimension most directly affected by effort near the threshold);
 (ii) prices do not change (because reducing
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

 alone was not sufficient to activate
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha>0$
\end_inset

);
 (iii) the quality improvement is concentrated at the lower tail of the distribution (farmers near 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{min}$
\end_inset

 adjust,
 while those already well above the threshold do not).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The enforcement channel explains the main experiment results:
 quality improves through more credible rejection threats,
 but prices do not differentiate.
 The model,
 however,
 also generates predictions about what would happen if quality-based pricing were activated,
 i.e.,
 if
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 were exogenously increased from zero.
 This motivates the follow-up experiment,
 which directly tests these predictions by providing quality premiums to traders.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Stronger Quality-based Incentives at the Aggregation Stage
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A higher 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 increases the value of quality for the MCC.
 As a result,
 MCCs may tighten acceptance standard,
 rejecting more low-quality milk and thereby increasing average quality 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{q}_{m}$
\end_inset

 among accepted deliveries.
 Second,
 when pass-through is positive 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\lambda_{i}>0\right)$
\end_inset

,
 higher 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 also raises farmer effort and individual quality 
\begin_inset Formula $q^{*}_{i}$
\end_inset

,
 further increasing 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{q}_{m}$
\end_inset

 and any intermediary outcome that is increasing in realized quality or quality-linked revenue
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial\bar{q_{m}}}{\partial\alpha}>0\label{eq:comp_stat_trans-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Response to Threshold Changes under Quality-based Pricing
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The model also generates predictions about how the behavioral response to quality-based pricing depends on the level of the acceptance threshold
\begin_inset Formula $q_{min}$
\end_inset

 relative to the prevailing quality distribution.
 When
\begin_inset Formula $q_{min}$
\end_inset

 is low relative to the natural distribution of quality (as when high-quality milk is abundant in the rainy season),
 most suppliers are comfortably above the threshold:

\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{i}\approx1$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula $\partial\pi_{i}/\partial e_{i}\approx0$
\end_inset

.
 In this regime,
 the extensive margin contributes little to the marginal return to effort.
 The intensive margin
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{i}\lambda_{i}\alpha\theta_{i}y_{i}$
\end_inset

 is active and rewards both higher quality (through the price gradient) and higher volume (since accepted milk earns the quality premium on every liter).
 The model is agnostic about which of these responses dominates:
 this depends on the relative costs of sourcing additional volume versus sourcing higher-quality milk,
 which are not pinned down by the model.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When
\begin_inset Formula $q_{min}$
\end_inset

 is raised (as when quality thresholds are tightened or when the dry season reduces the natural quality of available milk),
 a larger fraction of suppliers falls near or below the threshold.
 The acceptance probability
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{i}$
\end_inset

 drops below one for many suppliers,
 and the extensive margin
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial\pi_{i}}{\partial e_{i}}\left[p_{0}y_{i}+\lambda_{i}\alpha\theta_{i}e_{i}y_{i}\right]$
\end_inset

 strengthens.
 The model unambiguously predicts that raising the threshold increases the incentive to improve quality,
 since the threat of losing the entire bonus at the threshold creates a strong discrete incentive that complements the continuous gradient.
 Formally,
 the relative importance of the extensive margin in the first-order condition is increasing in
\begin_inset Formula $q_{min}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial}{\partial q_{min}}\left[\frac{\text{extensive margin}}{\text{total marginal return}}\right]>0
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The follow-up experiment varies the threshold across two stages.
 In Stage 1,
 the quality threshold is set at the East African standard (low
\begin_inset Formula $q_{min}$
\end_inset

);
 in Stage 2,
 the threshold is raised.
 The model predicts that quality-improving effort should be stronger in Stage 2,
 when the extensive margin is active.
 Whether quality also improves in Stage 1 (through the intensive margin alone) is an empirical question that depends on the cost structure of quality sourcing relative to volume expansion.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Farmer Responses to Stronger Downstream Incentives
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{i}>0$
\end_inset

,
