\begin_layout Section
Follow-up Experiment:
 Activating the Price Channel
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:experiment2"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Design
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:exp2-design"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The main experiment established that making quality observable through the measurement and digital monitoring system improved enforcement but did not,
 on its own,
 generate quality-based pricing.
 The follow-up experiment tests whether introducing explicit price incentives for quality can activate the price channel that remained dormant in the main experiment.
 We designed this as a lab-in-the-field experiment that builds directly on the infrastructure already deployed at treatment MCCs,
 exploiting the fact that milk analyzers and the digital record-keeping system were already operational at these sites.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We focus on 19 MCCs in the Kazo district where the quality measurement system from the main experiment was functioning reliably.
 Within each MCC,
 traders who deliver milk are randomized to treatment or control,
 with randomization stratified by MCC to ensure within-center comparisons.
 Treated traders receive a quality premium tied to their daily milk quality readings,
 while control traders continue under the status quo.
 Because randomization is within MCC,
 both groups face the same MCC-level conditions and price environment,
 isolating the effect of the quality premium itself.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The design exploits a repeated-game structure.
 Traders make daily decisions about where to source milk,
 how carefully to handle it,
 and how much to deliver,
 generating a panel of behavioral responses over approximately 30 days.
 This creates a rich setting for observing how supply chain actors respond to price incentives for quality in real time.
 A pre-announced mid-experiment threshold shift (from Stage 1 to Stage 2) functions as a within-experiment variation in the rules of the game,
 analogous to changing parameters across rounds in a laboratory experiment.
 This allows us to trace behavioral adjustment dynamics as the quality bar tightens,
 something that would be difficult to observe in a standard cross-sectional RCT.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Intervention
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:exp2-intervention"

\end_inset

Treated traders receive a quality premium of UGX 100 per liter for each 0.1 percentage point of fat and SNF content above the East African Community standards of 3.3 percent fat and 8.5 percent SNF.
 The premium is calculated automatically from the digital quality records already captured by the measurement system installed during the main experiment.
 Bonuses are paid daily via mobile money (using the Yo!
 Uganda API),
 creating immediate and salient incentives that traders can link directly to each day's delivery quality.
 The digital infrastructure from the main experiment is essential to this intervention:
 it provides the verifiable,
 timestamped quality records on which bonus calculations are based,
 and eliminates the need for any additional measurement or monitoring technology.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To illustrate the magnitude of the incentive,
 consider a trader collecting 500 liters per day with milk at 4.0 percent fat and 8.8 percent SNF.
 This trader would earn a daily bonus of approximately UGX 35,000 (roughly USD 9),
 a meaningful supplement to typical trading margins.
 The premium structure is linear and transparent:
 traders can calculate their expected bonus from the quality readings displayed on the analyzer after each delivery,
 reinforcing the connection between quality effort and financial reward.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The experiment proceeds in two stages.
 In Stage 1 (November 1 through 14),
 the quality thresholds are set at the East African Community standards:
 3.3 percent fat and 8.5 percent SNF.
 These thresholds are within reach for most traders delivering unadulterated milk,
 so Stage 1 primarily tests whether the existence of any quality premium induces behavioral change along the quantity or quality margins.
 In Stage 2 (beginning November 15),
 the fat threshold is raised to 3.9 percent while the SNF threshold remains unchanged.
 This increase was pre-announced to traders at the start of the experiment,
 simulating conditions analogous to dry-season quality tightening or a processor raising procurement standards.
 Stage 2 tests the intensive margin:
 whether traders can and do respond to a more demanding quality bar by sourcing higher-quality milk or improving handling practices.
 The within-experiment threshold change allows us to observe how the same traders adjust behavior when the rules of the game shift,
 providing a cleaner test of behavioral flexibility than a comparison across separate experiments would allow.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Sample and Timeline
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:exp2-sample"

\end_inset

The follow-up experiment draws on 19 MCCs in the Kazo district,
 a subset of the main experiment's treatment MCCs where the quality measurement and digital monitoring system remained operational.
 Within these MCCs,
 we identified approximately 100 traders and randomized them to treatment or control within MCC blocks,
 yielding 47 treated and 52 control traders.
 Power calculations using DeclareDesign indicated that with 100 traders and approximately 5 farmers per trader,
 assuming a 0.5 percentage point increase in fat content,
 70 percent pass-through from trader to farmer,
 and an intra-cluster correlation of 11 percent,
 the design would be adequately powered to detect meaningful quality effects.
 The total budget for quality premium payments was approximately USD 35,000,
 or roughly USD 200 per treated trader over the experiment period.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Baseline data collection took place in late October 2025.
 Stage 1 of the experiment began on November 1,
 2025,
 and the pre-announced threshold change marking Stage 2 took effect on November 15.
 The experiment concluded on approximately December 1,
 generating a total of 5,596 daily milk quality submissions recorded through the digital monitoring system.
 After filtering,
 the analysis sample comprises 2,622 trader-day observations:
 1,224 in Stage 1 and 1,351 in Stage 2,
 with the remainder falling on boundary days.
 Endline surveys were conducted in the final days of the experiment,
 covering 99 of the 100 targeted traders and 422 farmers (197 in treated trader catchments and 225 in control).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The combination of high-frequency digital records and endline survey data provides two complementary windows into the experiment's effects.
 The daily submission data,
 which includes fat content,
 SNF,
 and volume for each delivery,
 allows us to track behavioral dynamics within and across stages at fine temporal resolution.
 The endline surveys capture outcomes that the digital system does not record,
 including sourcing practices,
 farmer-trader relationships,
 and farmers' own production and marketing decisions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Outcome Variables
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:exp2-outcomes"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We measure outcomes at three levels,
 drawing on both administrative records and purpose-built endline surveys.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first source is the daily submission data recorded by the Lactoscan at each MCC,
 which yields the trader-day panel described above.
 For each delivery day we observe quantity-weighted average fat content (percent),
 quantity-weighted average solids-not-fat (SNF,
 percent),
 total liters delivered,
 and the quality bonus earned (UGX).
 Because these variables are generated by the measurement system itself,
 they are free of enumerator or recall bias.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The second source is the trader endline survey.
 Key outcomes include fat content from a supervised test conducted by the enumerator (an objective measure independent of routine MCC records),
 liters delivered on the day preceding the interview,
 whether any milk was rejected in the preceding month,
 whether the trader pays farmers a premium for quality,
 and the volume-weighted average price paid to supplying farmers (UGX per liter).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The third source is the farmer follow-up endline survey.
 Outcomes include the volume-weighted price received from the trader (UGX per liter,
 constructed from up to six recent transactions),
 whether quality was checked in any recent transaction,
 and a set of feeding practice indicators:
 use of bran,
 use of crop residues,
 use of mineral licks,
 and use of controlled grazing.
 We combine the four feeding indicators into an Anderson index to summarize investments in milk quality at the farm level.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Estimation and Inference
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:exp2-estimation"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the daily submission data,
 we estimate treatment effects using OLS with MCC fixed effects:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y_{jt}=\alpha+\beta\,\text{Treatment}_{j}+\mu_{m}+\varepsilon_{jt}\label{eq:exp2-daily}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where
\begin_inset Formula $y_{jt}$
\end_inset

 is the outcome for trader
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 on day
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Treatment}_{j}$
\end_inset

 is an indicator equal to one if trader
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 was assigned to receive quality bonuses,
 and
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{m}$
\end_inset

 is a fixed effect for the MCC at which trader
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 delivers.
 Because treatment was randomized within MCC,
 the MCC fixed effects absorb all time-invariant MCC-level confounders and increase precision.
 Standard errors are clustered at the trader level.
 We estimate this specification over three windows:
 the full post-treatment period (November 3 onward),
 Stage 1 only (November 3 through 14),
 and Stage 2 only (November 15 onward).
 Comparing coefficients across stages reveals whether traders adjust to the higher quality threshold.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the trader endline,
 we estimate an analogous specification with MCC fixed effects but without clustering,
 since traders are themselves the unit of randomization.
 For the farmer follow-up endline,
 the specification again includes MCC fixed effects,
 with standard errors clustered at the trader level to account for the nesting of farmers within trader catchments.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our primary inferential framework is Fisher randomization inference (RI),
 computed from 5,000 permutations of the treatment indicator within MCC blocks.
 To match the fixed-effects specification,
 outcomes are demeaned at the MCC level before computing the RI distribution.
 To account for multiple testing across outcomes within a family,
 we report Westfall-Young stepdown-adjusted p-values,
 which control the familywise error rate while exploiting the correlation structure across outcomes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Balance and Attrition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:exp2-balance"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Table
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:balance-exp2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 reports pre-treatment means and treatment-control differences for the three daily submission outcomes,
 estimated over the brief window before November 1 when deliveries were recorded but no bonuses had yet been activated.
 SNF and quantity show no significant differences between groups.
 Fat content,
 however,
 exhibits a statistically significant imbalance (
\begin_inset Formula $p=0.0004$
\end_inset

):
 control traders delivered milk with higher average fat (control mean of 4.06 percent) than treatment traders in this pre-period.
 This imbalance likely reflects the combination of a very short pre-treatment window (one to two delivery days) and a small number of traders,
 which leaves limited scope for the law of large numbers to equalize baseline quality across arms.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Several features of the design mitigate concern that this imbalance compromises identification.
 First,
 the MCC fixed effects in our estimating equation absorb any MCC-level differences in milk quality,
 so the treatment effect is identified from within-MCC variation between treated and control traders.
 Second,
 the comparison across Stage 1 and Stage 2 is particularly informative:
 because the same traders face both regimes,
 the stage-by-stage contrast traces behavioral dynamics within treated traders over time and does not rely on the level difference between treatment and control groups.
 Third,
 the Fisher randomization inference accounts for the within-MCC assignment structure,
 ensuring that p-values reflect the actual experimental variation rather than a hypothetical superpopulation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Attrition is minimal.
 The daily submission data are administrative records from the digital monitoring system,
 so they do not suffer from survey nonresponse.
 For the endline surveys,
 99 of the approximately 100 targeted traders were interviewed,
 and 422 of the approximately 500 targeted farmers completed the follow-up questionnaire (197 in treated trader catchments and 225 in control).
 The shortfall in the farmer sample reflects the difficulty of locating smallholder farmers who sell through mobile traders,
 rather than differential attrition by treatment status.
\end_layout

