\begin_layout Subsubsection
Trader Endline Survey
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Despite the strong effects in the daily submission data,
 the trader endline survey conducted after the experiment ended shows no significant treatment effects across any of the five outcomes:
 supervised fat content (p = 0.287),
 delivered quantity (p = 0.396),
 rejection rates (p = 0.691),
 whether the trader pays a quality premium (p = 0.155),
 and purchase price (p = 0.413).
 None of the five outcomes approaches conventional significance levels.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Three factors likely explain the divergence between the daily and survey results.
 First,
 the endline was conducted after the bonus period ended,
 so traders were no longer operating under the treatment incentive at the time of the survey.
 The null results are therefore consistent with a model in which behavioral responses to the bonus are contemporaneous rather than habit-forming.
 Second,
 the trader sample is small (99 traders,
 of whom only 30 have a supervised fat test),
 limiting statistical power for survey-based detection.
 Third,
 the daily submission data aggregate behavior over 30 days of repeated decisions,
 whereas the endline captures a single cross-sectional snapshot.
 Cumulative treatment effects visible in panel data can fall below detection thresholds in a one-time survey,
 particularly when the treatment has ended.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Farmer-Level Outcomes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We also examine whether the trader-level treatment generates downstream effects on the farmers from whom treated traders source milk.
 The most striking finding is a negative effect on farmer prices:
 farmers selling to treated traders report receiving 16.89 UGX less per liter (RI p = 0.017,
 WY p = 0.050).
 This negative pass-through is significant and runs counter to the prediction that quality premiums at the trader level would raise prices for farmers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Several mechanisms can rationalize this result.
 First,
 treated traders expand their sourcing networks (recruiting friends and family to deliver more milk),
 which increases the supply of milk available to the trader and shifts bargaining power away from individual farmers.
 Second,
 the quality bonus creates an incentive for traders to substitute from price competition to quality screening:
 rather than competing for farmer loyalty through higher prices,
 treated traders screen for quality and direct their collection toward farmers whose milk meets the threshold.
 Third,
 the bonus reward structure encourages sourcing from more farmers at the prevailing price (extensive-margin expansion) rather than paying existing farmers a premium.
 In each case,
 the surplus generated by the quality bonus accrues to the trader rather than passing through to farmers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Other farmer outcomes provide limited evidence of behavioral transmission.
 Whether the farmer reports having quality checked is unaffected by treatment (coefficient of -0.027,
 not significant).
 The feeding practices index shows a marginally significant improvement of 0.134 (RI p = 0.076,
 WY p = 0.145),
 though this does not survive multiple testing correction.
 No individual feeding practice is significant on its own.
 The marginal feeding index result suggests that some information about quality requirements may transmit from treated traders to their farmers,
 inducing modest adjustments in feeding behavior even in the absence of price incentives.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Summary
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The follow-up experiment confirms that activating the price channel through quality-contingent bonuses elicits rapid and substantial behavioral responses from traders.
 The Stage 1 versus Stage 2 contrast provides a clean test of the model's prediction:
 when quality is abundant relative to the threshold,
 traders respond on volume;
 when the threshold binds,
 they shift to quality-based sourcing.
 The daily panel reveals that these adjustments occur within days,
 consistent with the low adjustment costs inherent in trader sourcing decisions.
 At the same time,
 the surplus from quality bonuses does not pass through to farmers,
 and the effects do not persist into the post-treatment survey.
 Taken together,
 these findings indicate that while the price channel can activate quality-improving behavior at the trader level,
 sustaining and transmitting these effects through the supply chain requires incentive structures that operate continuously rather than temporarily.
\end_layout

