\begin_layout Subsection
Why Thresholds Drive Behavior More Than Gradients
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A striking pattern in the follow-up experiment is that traders respond to the threshold rather than the price gradient.
 The quality premium is a continuous function of compositional quality above the threshold:
 each 0.1 percentage point of fat above
\begin_inset Formula $q_{min}$
\end_inset

 earns an additional UGX 100 per liter.
 Under standard price theory,
 traders should always source higher-quality milk,
 since the gradient rewards every increment in fat content regardless of whether the threshold is low or high.
 Yet in Stage 1,
 when nearly all deliveries clear the threshold,
 traders expand volume rather than quality.
 Only when the threshold rises in Stage 2 and many deliveries fall below it do traders shift to quality-based sourcing.
 This suggests that the extensive margin (the discrete jump from zero to positive bonus at the threshold) dominates the intensive margin (the continuous gradient above it) in driving behavioral responses.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Several mechanisms could explain this pattern,
 and the daily submission data from the follow-up experiment allow us to begin distinguishing between them.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A first explanation draws on loss aversion and reference dependence.
 During Stage 1,
 traders become accustomed to receiving daily bonus payments via mobile money.
 When the threshold rises in Stage 2,
 deliveries that previously qualified suddenly earn zero.
 If traders evaluate outcomes relative to their Stage 1 reference point,
 the perceived loss from falling below the new threshold exceeds the foregone gain from not optimizing along the gradient in Stage 1.
 This predicts that traders who earned higher bonuses in Stage 1 should respond more strongly in Stage 2,
 since they have more to lose.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A second,
 related explanation emphasizes salience.
 The threshold creates a binary,
 immediately observable signal:
 the trader either qualifies or does not.
 The gradient requires calculating marginal returns to quality improvement,
 which is cognitively more demanding.
 If thresholds are more salient than gradients,
 traders should bunch just above the new threshold in Stage 2 rather than spread across the quality distribution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A third explanation is purely rational and based on the cost structure of quality sourcing.
 Improving average quality requires restructuring the supplier network:
 dropping low-quality farmers,
 recruiting new ones,
 or renegotiating terms.
 These adjustment costs are lumpy.
 In Stage 1,
 the marginal return from the gradient may not justify the fixed cost of network restructuring.
 In Stage 2,
 the total loss from falling below the threshold is large enough to warrant these costs.
 This predicts that the quality response should emerge gradually as traders reorganize sourcing,
 and that treated traders should change the composition of their supplier base between stages.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The time path of the quality response at the Stage 2 transition provides a first discriminating test.
 If the response is immediate (within days of the threshold change),
 this favors the behavioral explanations:
 loss aversion and salience can operate instantly because they require only a change in effort or attention,
 not a restructuring of supply networks.
 If instead the response is gradual (building over weeks),
 this points toward the cost-based explanation.
 An analysis of whether the composition of supplying farmers changes between stages provides a further test:
 if treated traders source from different farmers in Stage 2 than in Stage 1,
 the cost-based mechanism is at work;
 if the same farmers deliver higher-quality milk,
 the effect operates through effort rather than network restructuring.
 We leave these tests for future work.
\end_layout

