\begin_layout Standard
[Placeholder discussion section.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Key points to develop:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
1.
 The enforcement equilibrium:
 Why MCCs chose alpha = 0.
 The quality measurement and digital monitoring system leads to enforcement (rejection of adulterated milk,
 with digital records enabling systematic tracking) rather than price differentiation.
 This is consistent with models of collective action problems where MCCs have limited incentive to invest in quality-differentiated pricing when they can simply enforce minimum standards.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
2.
 Why alpha > 0 does not emerge endogenously.
 Possible explanations include:
 coordination failures among MCCs,
 limited downstream demand for quality differentiation from processors,
 farmer heterogeneity making graded pricing administratively costly,
 and social norms around uniform pricing in cooperatives.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
3.
 Policy implications.
 Deploying quality measurement and digital monitoring infrastructure is necessary but not sufficient for creating markets for quality.
 Even when quality is both measurable and digitally trackable,
 additional interventions that directly create price incentives (such as quality bonuses or graded pricing mandates) are needed to move from enforcement equilibria to quality-differentiated markets.
 This has implications for the design of quality infrastructure programs in developing country agricultural value chains.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
4.
 Revealed preference for quality measurement.
 The substantial contamination of the control group (24 percent of control MCCs had acquired a milk analyzer by endline,
 including five units originally provided through the project) provides indirect evidence that MCCs value quality measurement technology independently of any price channel.
 MCCs appear willing to invest in or acquire analyzers for their enforcement value alone,
 suggesting that the demand for quality infrastructure is real even when quality-differentiated pricing does not emerge.
 This is consistent with the model's prediction that the enforcement channel (reducing sigma-squared) generates value for MCCs through reduced rejection risk and improved screening,
 independent of the pricing parameter alpha.]
\end_layout

